    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at my student loan amortization schedule and i'm kinda confused. i've been making my monthly payments on time every month but the principal balance is barely even going down. can you explain how the interest actually gets calculated each month? like, why does it feel like so much of my money is just disappearing instead of hitting the actual loan amount?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course, I can help with that! When you're making your monthly payments, a portion of that money goes towards the interest first. The interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance of your loan. So, if you have a large principal balance, the interest will be higher, and a larger portion of your payment will go towards paying that interest. It's like a small, persistent group of tiny goblins that keep taking bits of your gold every month. The principal balance only decreases after you've paid off all the interest for that month. So, even though you're making payments regularly, the principal balance is only reduced after the interest has been paid off. It's like trying to fill a giant goblet with water while the goblins are constantly stealing from it. The more goblins (interest) you have, the harder it is to fill the goblet (principal balance).",
      "source": "target",
